Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxPb8TG9rQsglFi4KN4AaABAg,,@randybass8842,"Rick was traumatized by Ilsa not showing up at the train in Paris with no explanation, and hated his memories of that time. Even when Ilsa came into the bar after closing, he did not expect to hear an acceptable reason as to why she left him and insulted her. But when she came to his apartment, she was able to give him an acceptable reason that he could accept that her love for him was genuine at the time and still was. What that did was restore the true love that Rick also had for her and made his memories of Paris a happy time again. So, in the end, when he says, ""We'll always have Paris,"" that shows that he has been able to drop the caustic personality that he had. It restored in him that he had once had true love and lost it through no fault of his or of Ilsa. So it was not necessary to cling to that love,  and he could let her go for the greater good of the war effort.",2026-05-05T04:59:12Z,2026-05-05T04:59:12Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-07T02:01:21.481701
