Tourism,hBQ6ObjF3W8,UgxhqmTukui2V5zHtkx4AaABAg,,@ghill628,"9:16 - You've got it backwards, Caesars Entertainment used to be El Dorodo Resorts. It was the El Dorodo, the Carano family that purchased Caesars and the row as you call it, the El Dorado, Silver Legacy & Circus Circus were all connected long before that happened.
If you're listening to this guy about what's happening in Reno, you're woefully misinformed. The fact is, Reno doesn't rely on gambling anymore, the cities (Reno & Sparks) and the county began pushing for business growth and for the most part it's worked. That gaming sailed back in the 1980s when Reno figured out that they could never compete with Las Vegas. It became more pronounced when Indian & other gaming went nationwide in the 1990s. For all intents and purposes Reno is down to 5 casino; the El Dorodo/SIlver Legacy/Circus Circus, the Grand Sierra, The Peppermill, the Atlantis and the Nugget in Sparks. Reno is in no way shape or form analogous to Las Vegas and to compare the two is just dumb.",2026-05-06T21:18:23Z,2026-05-06T21:28:34Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-07T02:02:50.375278
