Tourisme,tQG5jBBGn2Q,Ugwajd5nmZA6azfm9UZ4AaABAg,,@ninny65,"This is quite interesting, shedding light on what the Apartheid government were trying to do, even though it could be seen also as an attempt to maintain federal control by giving devolving power to ethnic groups. It's ironic too, because even in modern day South Africa as we speak, there is movements attempting to separate the different black ethnic groups by Non-European descend peoples. We can see this with Operation Dudula and the March and March Movement. Data says roughly 26% of South Africans identify more strongly with their ethnic group than with their national identity, a sharp increase from previous decades. Only about 16% of citizens now value their national identity over their ethnicity. Only 31% of South Africans reporting that they trust members of other ethnic groups ""somewhat"" or ""a lot"". More than 40% of South Africans believe the government discriminates against their specific ethnic group. 

The political movement for the ""Rainbow Nation"" seems to not be as watertight as some might have hoped for. I think the problem is the movement was more aspirational than a revolution on rejecting tribal/ethnic identity. And politically speaking, simply a means to shift power away from the white minority",2026-05-06T21:43:10Z,2026-05-06T21:44:53Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-07T02:04:07.689942
